<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / International Company News: Exide set to buy Fiat battery
unit for Dollars 535m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Exide, the US maker of automotive batteries, is set to become Europe's
biggest car battery maker with the acquisition of a Fiat subsidiary for
Dollars 535m, writes Richard Waters.
The Michigan-based company said it had signed a letter of intent to buy Cia
Europeenne d'Accumulateurs (Ceac) from Fiat. With annual sales of some
Dollars 700m, Ceac is the current European market leader. It operates mainly
in France, Italy and Germany.
The deal is the third attempt by Exide to break into the European market in
recent months. In July it agreed to pay around Dollars 250m for Tudor, a
Spanish battery maker. Before that, it paid around Dollars 30m for Big
Batteries, a privately-owned Welsh company.
Exide said it would finance a 'significant' portion of the bid with equity,
and that it would borrow from banks and raise sub-ordinated debt for the
rest.
