<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / International Company News: Northwest Airlines maintains
advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Northwest Airlines yesterday reinforced the picture of recovery among the
big US carriers by reporting its highest-ever quarterly profits for the
three months to September.
Northwest said net income jumped from Dollars 110.7m to Dollars 170m in the
third quarter, its fifth consecutive profitable quarter.
The size of the increase echoed the figures reported a day earlier by
American Airlines, which increased net profits to Dollars 188m from Dollars
102m.
Northwest said revenues rose 6.5 per cent to Dollars 2.5bn and operating
profits rose 34 per cent to Dollars 359.2m. Earnings per share, fully
diluted, were up 19 per cent at Dollars 1.73.
Like American, Northwest has been responding to competition from smaller,
low-cost carriers in the US by cutting unprofitable routes and increasing
productivity in its remaining operations. It has also benefited from lower
fuel prices and economic growth.
Last year Northwest won a substantial reduction in its costs by reaching a
deal with its workforce in which it swapped a 27.4 per cent stake in the
company for wage cuts and other labour concessions worth Dollars 886m over
39 months.
The airline has also suffered less badly from low-cost competition than some
other big carriers. Many of the areas Northwest serves are less densely
populated and are therefore less suitable for the high-frequency, short-haul
shuttle services that low-cost operators offer.
Southwest Airlines, the biggest of the low-cost US carriers, continued its
strong profits growth with a 20 per cent increase in net income to Dollars
58.6m in the third quarter.
</TEXT>
