<DATE>941021
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / International Company News: Cellular phone grouping for US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Four US regional telephone companies are to form a partnership in cellular
telephones across the US, with almost 4m customers. The partners - Bell
Atlantic, Nynex, US West and AirTouch - will also bid jointly for personal
communication service (PCS) licences being auctioned off later this year by
the US government.
Bell Atlantic and Nynex, which serve most of the US eastern seaboard, had
already agreed to merge their cellular interests. Separately, so had US West
and AirTouch, which cover the West Coast. The new arrangement would not be a
merger, the partners said. However, it would launch a nationally branded
cellular service, possibly in combination with a long-distance phone company
as a further partner.
Referring to rumours that the Bell Atlantic/Nynex consortium had previously
been trying to do a deal with MCI, the second largest US long distance
company, the partners denied that their agreement represented a second best
option. The US telephone industry has been involved in a strenuous search
for partners since the recently completed merger of AT&amp;T with McCaw, which
puts together America's biggest long-distance company and biggest cellular
company.
'Everybody has been talking to everybody, and we are still talking,' one of
the partners said yesterday. 'But we feel we have the critical mass to go
alone if necessary.'
One of the attractions of merging with a long-distance partner, industry
observers said, was that only long-distance telephone companies such as AT&amp;T
or MCI had a nationally recognised brand name.
The partners said the new entity, provisionally known as Tomco, would bid
for PCS licences on the basis of filling in geographic areas where the
partners were not represented.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Bell Atlantic Corp.
    Nynex Corp.
    US West Inc.
    AirTouch Communications.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4812 Radiotelephone Communications.
</IN>
