<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / International Company News: Outsider named US Prudential
chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Prudential Insurance, the US's biggest retail financial services group,
yesterday named an outsider as chairman and chief executive for the first
time in its 119-year history.
The company said Mr Arthur Ryan, currently the number two at Chase
Manhattan, would take over when Mr Robert Winters, 62, retires on December
1.
The appointment of an outsider highlights the Prudential's expansion into
mutual funds, lending and other financial services beyond its core life
insurance business. In areas such as credit cards and mortgage lending, the
Prudential is in direct competition with banking groups such as Chase.
Mr Ryan faces the immediate task of retouching Prudential's tarnished
reputation, which has been sullied by a scandal at Prudential Securities,
its broking arm.
Last year, Prudential Securities agreed to pay up to Dollars 371m in fines
and restitution to settle charges that it defrauded hundreds of thousands of
investors in the early 1980s by selling them Dollars 8bn of high-risk
limited partnerships.
Although it wasn't directly involved in the scandal, the strength of the
Prudential Insurance name helped to bring investors into the partnerships.
Mr Winters, an actuary by training, had indicated that he would retire early
ever since becoming chairman six years ago, the Prudential said. It added
that the board had picked an outsider because 'he was the best man for the
job'.
Mr Ryan, 52, a banker with a reputation for toughness and strong operating
skills, will face a very different culture at Prudential.
The group, which is based in Newark, New Jersey, is a mutual institution,
owned by its 50m policyholders, with an approach to business sometimes
described as 'Prudential polite'. It employs more than 100,000 people and
had revenues of Dollars 45bn last year.
The new chairman said the Prudential would be 'a tough, focused competitor
with the highest standard of business ethics'.
He said that he would start by 'working intensively' to understand its
operations.
Mr Ryan and Mr Thomas Labrecque, Chase's chairman, have presided over a
strong recovery at the New York banking group. The group's cumbersome
structure was streamlined, with all line units around the world reporting to
Mr Ryan.
However, Mr Ryan's chances of taking over as chairman were thought to be
limited because the two men are only four years apart in age.
Mr Labrecque said last night that the relatively small gap between the men's
ages had 'undoubtedly been part of the issue for Art'. He said it meant that
'at some point it was inevitable' that Mr Ryan would seek the helm of
another company.
Chase said yesterday that it did not intend to name a replacement for Mr
Ryan, and was instead promoting the three executive vice-presidents
responsible for its main divisions to work directly under Mr Labrecque.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Prudential Insurance Co of America.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6311 Life Insurance.
    P6321 Accident and Health Insurance.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  Appointments.
</TP>
