<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / International Company News: SCA signals steep price rises
for newsprint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCA, one of Europe's largest paper companies, yesterday announced a 25 per
cent increase in continental European newsprint prices, and a 15 per cent
rise in the UK market. The changes will take effect from the end of this
year.
The company signalled the price rise as it embarks upon annual contract
negotiations with big newspaper proprietors over supplies. It said it was
determined to force through increases in the face of some resistance from
the large buyers.
'We've cut the prices by so much over the past couple of years - these
companies must realise we've got to raise prices as demand goes up,' said Mr
Ulf Frolander, SCA's graphic paper managing director.
He said intense competition had led to price discounts of DM40 (Dollars
26.60) a tonne since the end of 1992; the latest increase will recover about
DM20 a tonne.
However, big British newspaper publishers, which buy 75 per cent of UK
supplies, are likely to use their market clout to resist large price rises.
'It is unlikely the big publishers will pay those rises this year - they are
not expecting a hike of more than 7 per cent,' said Mr Tim Rothwell, paper
and packaging analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the London stockbrokers.
Newsprint producers are trying to recover rising costs after the doubling of
prices for virgin pulp this year. Waste paper costs have tripled. At the
same time, demand has finally caught up with the availability of newsprint
after many years of over-supply.
SCA says it has seen a 6 per cent increase in European newsprint demand this
year. Mr Rothwell points to a rise in UK consumption of 14 per cent in the
first half of the year. Nordic companies Norske Skog and Stora earlier
announced newsprint price rises of 15 to 20 per cent and other large
producers are expected to follow suit.
</TEXT>
