<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Blair puts fresh blood into shadow cabinet: 'Modernisers'
promoted to economic portfolios
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair yesterday announced a shake-up of the shadow cabinet designed
to promote fresh blood and put the main economic departments in the hands of
his close allies.
After a day of tortuous negotiations with the 18 shadow ministers elected by
Labour MPs on Wednesday, Mr Blair settled on a line-up in which only five
portfolios remain unchanged.
The core economic appointments went to Mr Gordon Brown, who remains shadow
chancellor, Ms Harriet Harman, who becomes shadow employment secretary, and
Mr Jack Cunningham, who takes over as shadow trade and industry secretary.
All three support the 'modernising' group which has helped Mr Blair to move
Labour away from its former tax and spend economic philosophy.
Mr Robin Cook, a traditionalist who had made plain his desire to remain
close to the heart of economic policymaking, moves from the DTI brief to
take over as shadow foreign secretary.
The move was described as a promotion, reflecting Mr Cook's achievement in
topping the poll for both the shadow cabinet and the MPs' section of the
party's national executive.
However, in a gesture to the traditionalists, Mr Cook has been promised
membership of a new economic policy sub-committee which will also include Mr
John Prescott, the traditionalist deputy leader.
The big loser appeared to be Mrs Margaret Beckett, the former acting leader,
who was re-elected to the shadow cabinet in second place, but failed to win
one of the three big jobs shadowing the Treasury, Home Office or Foreign
Office.
Mrs Beckett, who unsuccessfully contested the leadership on a broadly
traditionalist platform, was appointed shadow health secretary after failing
to persuade Mr Blair that her popularity deserved a greater reward.
Mr Jack Straw, a leading moderniser who ran Mr Blair's leadership campaign,
was promoted from environment to the Home Office portfolio, in spite of
polling poorly in the elections.
Ms Mo Mowlam, another moderniser, moves from national heritage to replace Mr
Kevin McNamara as shadow Northern Ireland secretary.
The shadow cabinet's leading leftwing members moved sideways. Mr David
Blunkett switched from health to education, Mr Michael Meacher from open
government to transport, and Ms Joan Lestor from the family to overseas
development.
Mr Chris Smith, formerly environmental protection spokesman, replaces Ms
Mowlam at national heritage; Mr Frank Dobson moves from transport to
environment and London; and Mrs Ann Taylor moves from education to leader of
the Commons and citizens' charter.
Mr Gavin Strang retains his agriculture brief, Mr Donald Dewar, social
security, Mr George Robertson, Scotland, Mr Ron Davies, Wales and Mr David
Clark, defence.
</TEXT>
