<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Bank loans boosted as credit growth remains subdued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank lending grew at a faster rate than expected in September, but the
overall growth of UK credit is still quite subdued.
Figures released by the Bank of England yesterday show that M4, the
government's measure of broad money supply, grew by a seasonally adjusted
0.4 per cent between August and September. Over the 12 months to September,
it has risen by 4.8 per cent, well towards the lower end of the government's
3 per cent to 9 per cent monitoring range.
Within the M4 total, sterling lending to the private sector - excluding
banks and building societies - rose by Pounds 3bn in September, the highest
monthly figure since December 1993.
The Bank of England figures appear to contradict statistics from the British
Bankers Association which show a rise in lending of only Pounds 183 in
September, down from Pounds 1.5bn in August. However, the association's
figures exclude building society lending and only cover the main British
banking groups. It appears that a wider spread between base rates and money
market rates in September caused borrowers to switch from major banks to
smaller banks in order to reduce their borrowing costs.
Even with the Pounds 3bn jump in September, the trend in growth of bank
lending remains very weak. Lending to the M4 private sector rose by 3.7 per
cent in the year to September.
Total M4 growth has been stronger than that for bank lending because of
'underfunding' by the government, which occurs when the Bank of England does
not sell enough gilts to cover the public sector borrowing requirement.
Association figures show that the corporate sector is continuing to repay
bank borrowing. There was a particularly high repayment of Pounds 719m by
the financial sector. The one exception was the manufacturing sector, which
borrowed a net Pounds 28m, having repaid Pounds 167m in August.
The personal sector continues to borrow, however, with lending for house
purchases rising by Pounds 659m and that for credit cards by Pounds 83m.
Mr Nigel Richardson, head of bond research at Yamaichi International Europe,
said that consumer credit growth was quite strong while corporations were
merely replacing bank debt with funding from sources such as bonds and
equities.
While broad money growth has been slow, narrow money growth (mainly notes
and coins) has been strong. The Bank of England yesterday revised up the
annual growth rate of M0 in September from 7.1 per cent to 7.2 per cent. The
government's monitoring range is 0 per cent to 4 per cent.
</TEXT>
