<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Rate rise damps mortgage lending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The rise in interest rates last month appears to have hit mortgage lending -
with commitments to new loans made by building societies in September
slipping from the previous month.
However, the rise of 0.5 of a percentage point in interest rates also helped
societies - by boosting the inflow of customer savings.
Statistics released yesterday by the Building Societies Association show
that net new commitments last month dropped to Pounds 2.97bn, compared with
Pounds 3.02bn in August. In 1993, the September figure was Pounds 2.56bn -
increased from Pounds 2.43bn in August.
The monthly loans figures are an important forward-looking indicator as they
translate into lending carried out in following weeks.
New net lending in September totalled Pounds 1.11bn, against Pounds 1.13bn
in August and just Pounds 747m in September last year.
In spite of the slight month-on-month drop in both gross and net new loans
Mr Adrian Coles, the association's director-general, sounded upbeat. He said
levels of lending were now close to those in 1992 and significantly higher
than in the same period last year.
But he warned that the 'cautious, yet relatively stable market' could be
damaged by further rises in interest rates.
He said the growth in lending probably meant societies were recovering
market-share, rather than that the market was improving. Last summer the
popularity of fixed-rate mortgages offered by banks severely hit societies'
lending.
The higher rates societies were able to offer on deposits after the rise in
base rates helped them to attract more savings. Net retail receipts totalled
Pounds 322m - the highest monthly level since May and more than three times
the August figure of Pounds 91m.
Seasonal factors were also an element - savings usually increase at this
time of year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6162 Mortgage Bankers and Correspondents.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>ECON  Economic Indicators.
    STATS  Statistics.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
