<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Crackdown on data crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tougher penalties for selling confidential financial information obtained by
deception - such as details of a company's bank account - were approved by
the Commons last night.
Conviction on indictment could result in a maximum term of five years'
imprisonment and a fine under a Lords amendment to the criminal justice and
public order bill which was approved by MPs.
However, a Lords' amendment to make selling confidential financial
information a criminal offence was rejected.
Mr David Maclean, Home Office minister, said the proposed amendment went
beyond recommendations to counter unjustified invasion of privacy made by
the committee headed by Sir David Calcutt.
However, he suggested that it might be necessary to return to the rejected
amendment if some of the Calcutt proposals were not introduced.
The government secured a majority of 33 to reject a Labour attempt to make
it an offence to provide information obtained by deceit even if it was not
sold.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour spokesman on city affairs, referred to
advertisements offering to find out a person's bank balance for Pounds 250.
Mr Darling complained that the provisions introduced by the government would
not prevent information being obtained in written form so that no
infringement of the Data Protection Act would be involved.
</TEXT>
