<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / MPs slam costs of defence orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Taxpayers have forfeited millions of pounds and important weapon systems
have been unnecessarily delayed because of poor management and 'incredible'
errors, according to a Commons defence committee report.
In a detailed study of four kinds of military equipment, the MPs call for
the civil servants responsible for such mistakes to be 'reprimanded or
otherwise penalised'.
The committee found that the cost of developing an earth station to receive
signals from military satellites had ballooned by 62 per cent to Pounds 99m
because the project had not been properly defined in advance.
The price of a new system to scatter mines from a vehicle had also risen
'significantly' from Pounds 37m. The Ministry of Defence was 'in some
confusion' over how to explain this, according to the report.
The committee sharply criticises the ministry's rejection of an offer by
International Business Machines of a flexible, inflation-linked price in a
contract for 44 Merlin helicopters. The ministry's failure to examine IBM's
offer fully was described as 'grossly negligent' behaviour which might have
cost up to Pounds 95m.
However the committee acknowledges that new procedures, introduced at the
ministry over the past year, should avoid such mistakes in future.
Analysing the multinational project to make Trigat anti-tank missiles, the
committee notes that Britain found itself helping to develop a weapon which
it might not need.
But after negotiations on price the ministry concluded it would be cheaper
to stay in.
'The Ministry of Defence has found itself in the highly unusual position of
continuing to participate in the development programme for a missile for
which it has no specific programme,' the report notes.
House of Commons Defence Committee, 10th Report. Defence Procurement:
Certain projects and accounting for inflation. HMSO. Pounds 12.15.
</TEXT>
