<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Westminster 'planned illicit housing policies'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROB EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Westminster Conservative councillors planned an 'illicit' use of housing
policies to gentrify marginal wards to win a closely fought election, it was
claimed on the second day of public hearings into gerrymandering
allegations.
Mr Andrew Arden, acting for the objectors who made the original
gerrymandering allegations, highlighted a series of confidential documents
written by leading councillors on how to win the 1990 local elections.
Mr Arden described how the strategy documents 'succinctly' set out an
'illicit' policy to sell council homes in eight marginal wards, based on the
assumption that the buyers were more likely to vote Tory.
One document circulated in September 1986 by the then leader of the council,
Dame Shirley Porter, said: 'What is gentrification? In short, it is ensuring
that the right people live in the right areas. The areas are relatively easy
to define: target wards identified on the basis of electoral trends and
results.'
The same document said Tory councillors were commissioning a report from an
outside group - PA Cambridge Economic Consultants - which would help 'to
define which initiatives are most likely to produce the desired results'. Mr
Arden said one of the consultants was briefed by Dame Shirley. Notes of this
meeting recorded that the Conservatives' strategy was to 'push Labour voters
out of marginal wards' and 'boot out certain categories' of residents.
But the consultants' report highlighted the need to maintain the number of
homes available for renting. Mr Arden said the Tory councillors found the
report 'disappointing'.
One confidential document from January 1987 advocated that 'the short-term
objective must be to target the marginal wards, and as a matter of utmost
urgency, redress the imbalance by encouraging a pattern of tenure which is
more likely to translate into Conservative votes'.
In his report in January the district auditor, Mr John Magill, found
provisionally that Dame Shirley and nine others had wasted Pounds 21m on
selling off the homes. These accusations are denied. The hearings continue
today.
</TEXT>
