<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / City jobs scheme far short of targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Only 16 local people were offered jobs in the City of London during the
first year of Local Recruitment Brokerage, a non-profit making company
backed by the Bank of England which aims to recruit from neighbouring areas
with high unemployment.
The target figure for job offers had been 200. 'We were over-ambitious,'
said Ms Sharon Collins, the company's managing director, yesterday.
A total of 122 job vacancies were advertised through the brokerage by 49
City employers. As many as 620 candidates submitted applications, of whom
115 were interviewed and 16 were offered jobs. But Ms Collins said the
placement level had improved substantially over the past six months, with 18
offered jobs out of 250 applicants for 70 posts.
'Local people have not been used to the City's corporate culture,' Ms
Collins said. 'Companies are not going to change their attitudes overnight
either.'
The Brokerage is a partnership between City companies Kleinwort Benson, SG
Warburg, KPMG Peat Marwick, the Bank of England and the Corporation of
London in alliance with local authorities in Hackney and Islington and the
local training and enterprise council.
Companies participating in the scheme include Abbey National, KPMG, Midland
Bank, Baring Brothers, Merrill Lynch and Royal Insurance.
Ms Collins said yesterday that the company had become 'more pro-active' in
helping candidates to prepare their job applications and interview
techniques.
It is also establishing a computerised database of vacancies.
Mr Mike Ireland, the Bank of England's community relations director, has
replaced Mr Gareth Hughes as the company's chairman.
</TEXT>
