<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Business blow for 'dapper' lobbyist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At least one of the clients of Ian Greer Associates yesterday said it was
considering severing its links with the lobbyists at the centre of the
cash-for-questions allegations.
IGA, which denies allegations that it was the channel for payments to MPs in
return for parliamentary questions, is one of the longest-established and
most influential of the lobbying groups. It numbers among its clients
British Airways, British Gas, Cadbury Schweppes and Kingfisher.
One corporation said yesterday: 'A lot of Ian Greer's major clients will be
embarrased by this. It could be very damaging to his business. You're
innocent until you're proved guilty, but I'm sure a lot of people are
thinking very carefully.'
Yesterday's comments were the first indication that IGA may have to fight to
maintain its position.
Mr Greer, a former Tory party agent, has established a formidable track
record since he founded his company in 1982. Known for his attention to
detail and his understanding of the way Whitehall works, his list of
contacts is thought to be unrivalled.
One client said: 'He's got a considerable amount of political clout. He has
had a very good reputation for helping people to get their point across.
He's a dapper little chap - rather serious.'
Mr Steve Bevan, reporter with PR Week, described Mr Greer as 'charming,
autocratic and inspiring fierce loyalty' among his
Mr Bevan said that Mr Greer' strong links with the Tory party could pose a
problem in the future. 'Not only did he lend John Major a car during the
election, he is even rumoured to have driven it himself,' he said.
'But as companies wake up to the fact that there's a strong possibility of a
Labour government, they may consider moving to lobbyists considered to have
better Labour party links.'
According to one senior public relations executive with a close knowledge of
lobbying, Mr Greer specialised in cultivating an 'old-boy network'.
IGA is one of five groups which recently founded a trade association and
launched a code of conduct banning all financial links with MPs.
Mr Andrew Gifford, group chairman, said at the time: 'With attention on MPs
and their outside interests growing, a great deal of confusion has arisen
over the relationship between lobbyists and MPs. By establishing a register
of lobbyists . . . we hope to separate two distinct issues - the activities
of professional lobbyists on the one hand and the outside interests of MPs
on the other.'
</TEXT>
