<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Parade of ministers passes through
doorway marked exit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tim Smith is the 11th member of the government to leave office for
non-political reasons since Mr John Major succeeded Baroness (then Mrs)
Thatcher as prime minister in 1990.
Almost all have quit following allegations about their private lives or
claims that they had benefited financially from unethical behaviour.
Most have denied any wrongdoing, but decided to return to the backbenches to
limit the political damage to the government.
Most of the resignations have occurred since last year's Tory party
conference in Blackpool when Mr Major launched his much-derided
Back-to-Basics initiative.
The campaign has been a big casualty of the spate of disclosures and
resignation.
The other is Mr Major, whose efforts to draw a line under government
failures have been undermined by a parade of embarrassed ministers:
Mr David Mellor, heritage secretary, quit in September 1992 after an
onslaught by the tabloid papers over allegations of an affair with an
actress.
Mr Mellor, who denied any impropriety, resigned after it emerged that he had
accepted a paid holiday from the daughter of a member of the Palestine
Liberation Organisation.
Mr Michael Mates, Northern Ireland minister, quit in June 1993 after
revelations about his relationship with the fugitive businessman Mr Asil
Nadir. Mr Mates, who denied any wrongdoing, was seriously damaged by the
disclosure that he sent Mr Nadir a watch inscribed 'don't let the buggers
get you down'.
Mr Tim Yeo, countryside minister, quit in January after disclosures about an
extra-marital affair. Mr Yeo said his private life had not affected his
ability to do his job. Lord Caithness resigned as a transport minister in
January after the suicide of his wife. His resignation was followed by
newspaper speculation about his private life.
Mr Alan Duncan resigned as a parliamentary private secretary in January
after it emerged that he had lent money to a neighbour to buy a house from
Westminster City Council at a discount, and that Mr Duncan had then bought
the house from him. He denies any wrongdoing.
Mr David Ashby resigned as a PPS in January after admitting sharing a bed
with a man during a holiday in France. Mr Ashby denies any impropriety.
Mr Hartley Booth, Finchley MP, resigned as a PPS after newspaper disclosures
of his friendship with a female Commons researcher. Mr Booth denied having
an affair.
Mr Michael Brown resigned as a whip in May after allegations in a Sunday
newspaper that he had had a homosexual relationship with a student. Mr Brown
denied any impropriety.
Mr David Tredinnick and Mr Graham Riddick were suspended as PPSs in July
pending an inquiry into newspaper allegations that they were prepared to
accept Pounds 1,000 each to table parliamentary questions.
Mr Tim Devlin, a junior whip, was involved in a row with the government's
business managers in July when he announced he had resigned over defence
cuts, only for the whips to announce that he had been sacked.
Lord Archer, former deputy party chairman, failed to achieve promotion
earlier this year after disclosures about his share-dealing activities. He
denies any impropriety.
</TEXT>
