<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Blair gives Major blueprint for
raising standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair yesterday set out Labour's proposals for raising standards in
public life as he warned Mr John Major that his government was becoming
tainted by allegations of sleaze.
Speaking at prime minister's question time, the Labour leader put forward a
three-point plan to restore 'the confidence of the British people in their
government'.
His move came as it emerged that a future Labour government would probably
force companies to ballot shareholders before making political donations.
Mr Blair's proposals were:
No minister who has privatised a company should subsequently be allowed to
sit on its board.
A list of all members of quangos, payments, perks and any position with any
political party should be published by the government;
The 'cash-for-questions' inquiry should be broadened, 'held in public and be
made fully independent'.
Mr Blair said he noted the resignation of Mr Tim Smith as Northern Ireland
minister and awaited the outcome of investigations into Mr Neil Hamilton.
Earlier Mr John Prescott, Labour's deputy leader, said that the party's
general election manifesto would 'be giving serious attention' to the
question of balloting shareholders on the issue of political donations.
Referring to an 'imbalance' in the treatment of political donations from
companies and trade unions, Mr Prescott said it was not a situation that
Labour was 'prepared to allow to continue'.
Meanwhile Labour stepped up its attack on the government over sleaze by
launching a study of links between appointees to quangos and the
Conservative party.
The party said the study showed 'in graphic detail' how government
appointees to quangos were 'inextricably linked' to the financing of the
Conservative party.
Mr George Howarth, MP for Knowsley North who wrote the study, said: 'What is
truly scandalous is that none of these relationships or placements is
actually illegal.'
Labour called for those serving on quangos to be subject to the same
financial liability as local councillors and for the supervisory role of
select committees to be strength-ened.
Arguing that parliamentary scrutiny was no longer enough, Mr Prescott called
for Mr John Major, the prime minister, to set up an independent assessment
of standards of government and public life. The House of Commons' most
influential select committee is set to investigate a controversial decision
to give the vice-chancellor of Huddersfield University a severance payment
of more than Pounds 400,000.
The public accounts committee has received the green light to investigate
the severance payment recently promised to Professor Kenneth Durrands.
The inquiry by the committee will follow one to be carried out by the
National Audit Office, the government spending watchdog. The NAO yesterday
announced that it will carry out a preliminary investigation into the
broader context of the decision to make the payment.
</TEXT>
