<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 94 / Europe boosts its Security Council weight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Germany and Italy were elected to the UN Security Council last night, giving
Europe 40 per cent of the seats when they begin their two-year terms in
1995. Britain, France and Russia are permanent members and the Czech
Republic then will be in the second year of its term. Secret balloting was
conducted in the General Assembly following nominations by regional groups.
Indonesia, Botswana and Honduras also were elected.
The fact that the European Union's four principal states will be members for
the next two years can only add to a growing clamour by third world
countries for a radical restructuring of the council. Discussions that have
been going on for some time have made little progress, in part because of
disagreement about the size of an expanded council. While Germany and Japan
seem likely eventually to be admitted as permanent members, many delegates
say claims by big countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America must be
considered for a similar status.
</TEXT>
