Sysco, the biggest US distributor of food to restaurants, hotels, schools
and other places where people eat away from home, reported a 21 per cent
increase in net profits to Dollars 58.4m in its first quarter, writes
Richard Tomkins.
The comparison was flattered by an extra tax charge of Dollars 4.9m in the
comparable quarter which reduced net profits to Dollars 48.1m. But Sysco
said the pre-tax figure was more than 10 per cent ahead even after incurring
start-up costs on significant new business.
In the latest quarter, sales increased by 10 per cent to Dollars 2.98bn. Mr
John Woodhouse, chairman, said that real volumes, after adjusting for food
price inflation of 1.8 per cent, were up 8.3 per cent.
