<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / International Company News: Solid advances at GM
subsidiaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Revenues at EDS, the computer services subsidiary of General Motors, climbed
23 per cent in the latest quarter from a year ago, to Dollars 2.56bn.
Mr Les Alberthal, chairman and chief executive, attributed the advance in
sales to strong growth in Europe and Asia, adding that the value of new
business won in the first nine months of this year, at Dollars 7.4bn, was
already ahead of the figure for the whole of 1993.
The growth in sales supported a 13 per cent increase in after-tax profits
during the third quarter, to Dollars 216.4m. EDS's profits are used to
calculate the earnings of General Motors Class E shares, which were up 5
cents at 45 cents.
Meanwhile, General Motors Acceptance Corporation, the carmaker's financial
services arm, reported after-tax profits of Dollars 245m, up from Dollars
205m a year ago.
The company attributed the advance largely to lower funding costs, which
resulted from both a better funding mix than a year ago and greater
confidence among investors in the outlook for GMAC and its parent.
The financing company also benefited from higher vehicle sales and the
growing popularity of leasing. The number of vehicles leased worldwide more
than doubled compared with a year ago, to 168,000, GMAC said.
Last year, GMAC, EDS and GM Hughes Electronics contributed Dollars 2.6bn
between them to GM's profits, while the group as a whole reported total net
income of Dollars 2.5bn. GM reports third-quarter earnings today.
</TEXT>
