FT  20 OCT 94 / International Company News: CNP advances 14.9% to FFr691.5m
midway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Caisse Nationale de Prevoyance, the French state-owned insurance group,
achieved net profits of FFr691.5m (Dollars 130.71m) in the first half of the
year, a 14.9 per cent rise over the same period in 1993, writes John Ridding
in Paris.
Mr Pierre Darnis, chairman, said the increase in profits was achieved on
revenues of FFr39.6bn, a rise of 19 per cent over the first six months of
last year.
The insurance group is being prepared for a partial privatisation, which is
expected to take place by the end of the year.
Under the terms of the operation, the government will reduce its 42.5 per
cent direct holding in the company. However, the state will retain control
of the group through indirect investments via the post office and the Caisse
des Depots, the state financial institution.
Observers believe the state will sell about 30 per cent of CNP's capital,
which would bring estimated receipts of about FFr4bn. Analysts have valued
the company as a whole at about FFr12bn.
CNP, which specialises in life insurance products, has enjoyed rapid growth
over recent years, increasing its sales by more than 50 per cent in 1993 to
FFr64.3bn. It achieves most of its sales through post office and savings
bank branches and through tax offices.
