<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Blair's allies to get economic role in shadow cabinet
changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair will today carry out an important reconstruction of the shadow
cabinet with the aim of tightening his grip on Labour's economic strategy.
After Labour MPs last night made three changes to the 18-strong shadow
cabinet, the Labour leader was expected to put allies in all mainstream
economic portfolios.
Mr Gordon Brown will stay as shadow chancellor. Ms Harriet Harman will
probably move to shadow Mr Michael Portillo in employment. Mr Donald Dewar
is to stay at social security, with Mr Jack Cunningham possibly taking over
at trade and industry.
That would leave all economic portfolios in the hands of the party's
modernising wing.
Mr Cunningham's certain move from shadow foreign secretary would make room
for Mr Robin Cook, the traditionalist who topped the poll for the second
year running, to replace him.
The main uncertainties after last night's result, which saw the election of
a record five women, seemed to be over home affairs and education. Mr Jack
Straw, currently shadow environment spokesman, was being tipped by some to
take over as shadow home secretary, in spite of his surprisingly weak
performance in the election.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the former deputy leader who was re-elected in second
spot, would be a strong candidate for either post. Ms Mo Mowlam, shadow
heritage secretary, is another possible contender to replace Mrs Ann Taylor
in education.
There was disappointment for Mr Blair in that younger allies - Mr Brian
Wilson, Mr Alistair Darling and Mr Alun Michael - failed to be elected.
They are expected to secure important jobs on Labour's front bench when Mr
Blair reallocates the lower-ranking portfolios.
The result, which saw only one MP - Mr Tom Clarke - leave the shadow
cabinet, was being portrayed by the leadership as the consolidation of a
strong team.
As well as the return of Ms Harman and Mrs Beckett, the ballot saw the
election of Mr Gavin Strang, MP for Edinburgh East and shadow agriculture
spokesman.
The results (in order of votes received): Mr Robin Cook, Mrs Margaret
Beckett, Mr Gordon Brown, Mr Donald Dewar, Ms Harriet Harman, Mr Frank
Dobson, Mr George Robertson, Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Mr Chris Smith, Mr Jack
Cunningham, Mr Michael Meacher, Mr Ron Davies, Mr David Clark, Mr Jack
Straw, Mr David Blunkett, Ms Joan Lestor, Mr Gavin Strang, Mrs Ann Taylor.
