<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The move away from serious analysis in television journalism and towards
'human interest' material has turned into a trot. Stand by for the gallop.
BBC1 begins another series of Children's Hospital which has the attractions
of any medical series (high drama, bags of emotion) but also the special
advantages that come with child patients: they look appealing and tend to
die less often than the elderly (8.00). Blues And Twos is yet another of the
rash of ambulance-chasing series which have burst out all over television.
Today they chase paramedic Allan Norman as he races around London on a
motorbike reaching casualties much quicker than a four-wheeled ambulance.
Ironically he drives to work on an 80cc Yamaha but for the job he rides a
Honda 1100 (8.30 ITV). Inside Story offers yet another report on cosmetic
surgery; a subject upon which Alan Whicker made the definitive programme
years ago (10.00 BBC1). Prostitute is the last of a three-part French series
about 'the oldest profession' (11.05 C4). On second thoughts perhaps we are
already seeing the gallop.
</TEXT>
