<PROFILE>_AN-EJTEUACXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941020
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Civil Service Reorganisation: Mandarins try to please the
critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHANIE FLANDERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury has traditionally been the most powerful - and most often
criticised - of all government departments.
For many its role in economic policy-making is both outdated and
inefficient. Seen in that light yesterday's proposals are the mandarins'
attempt to redefine their role for the modern era, before less sympathetic
members of the government do it for them.
The department has always been a peculiarly British institution, with a
monopoly on all aspects of national economic management not seen elsewhere.
Most other countries tend to divide economic policy-making between a finance
ministry, an economics ministry and a separate budget office for the control
of public spending. The Treasury combines all three roles, as well as
managing civil service pay, regulating financial services and preparing
economic forecasts.
There has been a long-running debate about whether so much power should be
concentrated in the hands of one ministry. Mr Harold (now Lord) Wilson, for
one, attempted to hive off some of its functions to a new Department of
Economic Affairs in 1964 but was eventually forced to return to the old
system after vigorous Treasury resistance.
In spite of the Treasury winning these and other battles with individual
governments, three broad criticisms of its performance have refused to go
away. The first is that its power has given it much of the responsibility
for the damaging 'boom and bust' cycles of UK economic activity since the
early 1970s. Two humiliating events are particularly associated with
Treasury mistakes - the recourse to the International Monetary Fund in 1976
and sterling's departure from the European Exchange Rate Mechanism in
September of 1992.
Second, business leaders and others complain of the Treasury's
'anti-industry culture', blaming Treasury tax and spending decisions for the
declining competitiveness of UK manufacturing.
Third, and perhaps most relevant to yesterday's review, is the accusation
that the Treasury has a penny-pinching, short-termist and interfering
approach to the work of other government departments.
Losing control of public spending in the 1970s was a scarring experience.
Many officials drew the lesson that they would have to involve themselves
more deeply in every layer of government to ensure that public spending
never again spiralled out of control. The upshot, however, is that the
Treasury now tries to shadow officials in other departments, duplicating
their activities unnecessarily and, according to many civil servants, too
often meddling in their decisions.
If sterling's exit from the ERM cast doubt on the Treasury's capacity for
macroeconomic management, the civil service reforms of the Major government
have put a question mark over the Treasury's capacity for this kind of
microeconomic supervision.
Yesterday's proposals indicate that the department has seen the need to
reappraise its activities in light of recent experience. The increasing
decentralisation of public-sector pay bargaining and the more powerful
position which the Bank of England has acquired in the past two years might
mean that the Treasury cannot hope to continue performing all its
traditional functions. But Sir Terry Burns, its permanent secretary,
believes the Treasury's more all-encompassing conception can be defended.
The department must change, but Sir Terry believes that reform need not
imply a pared-down ministry along the lines of a Continental-style finance
ministry. He believes that, in spite of recent events, the Treasury should
not remodel itself as merely the finance department of UK plc. Rather, it
must remain the head office for the economy.
Sir Terry outlined this vision of the Treasury in a speech given earlier
this year. The great advantage which the Treasury had, he said, lay in its
freedom from outside pressures in its analysis of government activities.
'Most departments have their own special interest groups and serving those
groups can inhibit them in their attitude to change. The Treasury, by
contrast, serves no special interest group, which gives it the freedom to
promote change and to protect the dispersed interests of consumers and
taxpayers.'
Yesterday saw the Treasury apply both these precepts to its own activities.
It remains to be seen whether the new arrangement will satisfy the critics.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-15043</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EJTEUACWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941020
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Civil Service Reorganisation: Treasury cuts herald Whitehall
reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's announcement of a radical transformation in the role and
staffing of the Treasury could mark a defining moment in the history of
Britain's civil service.
The Treasury is at the pinnacle of the Whitehall pyramid. Few doubt that
with the reform starting there, pressure in Whitehall to slash senior posts
and reshape departments will become irresistible.
The aim of the Whitehall reform programme was set out in July's white paper
on the future of the civil service. It is to remove 'unnecessary layers of
management' from central government departments and to define more closely
than previously the functions of senior officials. It says baldly: 'The
government believes it will be in the national interest to have over a
period a somewhat smaller but better-paid senior civil service.'
According to those engaged in departmental reviews the result could be the
shedding of about one third of the 3,000 mandarins at grade 5 and above -
Whitehall's cream - with a significant impact on jobs at lower levels.
Although the most significant department to cut so far, the Treasury is not
the first to announce big job reductions at the top. In May the Department
of Transport unveiled a two-year 'streamlining' which will lead to the loss
of about a fifth of the department's 15,000 staff. Large-scale job cuts have
also been mooted at the environment and health departments, and almost every
part of Whitehall is at some stage in a senior management review.
The rationale for the reviews is partly political and partly managerial. At
the political level ministers are acutely conscious of the contrast between
Tory rhetoric about 'small government' and the reality that the number of
non-industrial civil servants has fallen by barely 10 per cent since
Baroness Thatcher took office in 1979. Industrial civil servants have borne
the brunt of cuts - the early 1990s even saw an increase in the number of
non-industrial staff.
The managerial imperative flows from the industry-wide drive to devolve
responsibility for service delivery to line managers, and to relate 'head
office' functions more closely to core responsibilities.
As Sir Terry Burns, permanent secretary to the Treasury, said in a lecture
this May to Durham University Business School: 'We have seen a shift away
from the 'command and control' style of management towards much greater
emphasis on decentralisation.' He said this resulted in 'a more contractual
approach of setting objectives against which management units might be
judged'.
A further pressure on ministers and departments is the freeze in civil
service running costs announced in last November's Budget. As resources fall
in real terms over the next four years staff will nonetheless be expected to
achieve constant improvements in the quality of service, in line with the
Citizen's Charter. To help them, government departments will be given
greater freedom over budgets, including the right to decide the salaries and
grading of staff, whose pay makes up more than half of civil service running
costs.
As part of the same process, permanent secretaries are being encouraged to
'de-layer' - reorganise their management structures with fewer grades - and
to impose personal contracts that emphasise the responsibilities of
officials to manage.
This means that Whitehall will be taking the same bitter medicine it has
imposed on the rest of the public service.
Yet pressure for reform does not stop there. A report of the Cabinet Office
Efficiency Unit last November wanted more top Whitehall jobs to be
advertised openly to ensure that non-Whitehall candidates were considered.
As the steamroller advances, the Whitehall 'career for life' will be
endangered - and some fear that the non-political status of the civil
service may come into question.
</TEXT>
