<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Civil Service Reorganisation: SIB may be given expanded
function
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury has proposed devolving more of its regulatory powers under the
Financial Services Act to the Securities and Investments Board, while taking
on additional duties for itself regulating occupational pensions and
insurance.
The Treasury's proposal to devolve more of its duties to SIB is seen as a
vote of confidence in SIB's activities.
In its review document released yesterday the Treasury proposed three key
areas where it felt SIB could expand its role. The Treasury said its
director of finance regulation and industry should review whether additional
work could be passed to SIB without primary legislation.
In particular, the Treasury would pass on the day-to-day responsibility for
overseeing the listing department of the London Stock Exchange, a move which
would make SIB more like the US Securities and Exchange Commission.
Such a development is unlikely to be welcomed by the exchange, which is
under pressure from SIB to alter some of its rules on the transparency of
transactions.
Moreover, the move would create additional expense for the exchange because,
unlike the Treasury, where costs are paid for out of tax revenues, SIB must
recover the costs of its activities from the regulated bodies themselves.
The Treasury said it would like to pass on the responsibility for
determining whether the rules and operation of overseas exchanges that wish
to conduct investment business in the UK are as rigorous as those of
domestic exchanges. While SIB already has a consulting role in making these
decisions, the Treasury is the final arbiter.
The Treasury has also proposed that SIB take on responsibility for
determining which territories offer equivalent investor protection to that
in the UK. Investment businesses from equivalently-regulated territories may
be allowed to operate in Britain.
Senior Treasury officials had been hinting for months that they believed
responsibility for regulation of occupational pensions and prudential
supervision of life assurance companies should be concentrated in its
department.
Yesterday's document said: 'In particular we see considerable logic and
attractions in the suggestion that the Treasury might eventually take on
more responsibility, for example, for the regulation of pensions and
insurance. Such a move would bring responsibility for regulating all the key
financial institutions and markets into one department, the Treasury.'
Sources familiar with the Treasury plans said the department expects to
provide oversight for the proposed new occupational pensions regulator to be
created through legislation in this parliamentary session. Responsibility
for occupational pensions currently rests with the Department of Social
Services, while the Department of Trade and Industry is responsible for the
prudential supervision of life insurance companies.
The DSS said yesterday: 'This is a Treasury internal document. The proposal
in question would be for discussion and concerns a possible change for the
future. The organisation of government is not for a single department to
decide.'
</TEXT>
