<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Civil Service Reorganisation: Officials put a brave face on
redundancy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stiff upper lips were in evidence at the Treasury yesterday as officials
reacted philosophically to news of swingeing job cuts.
An official whose job is in the firing line said: 'One has got to be
intellectually honest about this. There are one or two details about the
proposals which I disagree with, but the overall goal of cutting down on
management layers in the civil service is something hard to argue against.'
Such stoicism was the order of the day throughout the department, with
officials mindful that the medicine they were being forced to swallow was
precisely the stuff they had dosed out to other government departments for a
decade in the cause of greater public sector efficiency.
Another high-ranking civil servant said: 'A lot of people can see the logic
behind the moves, even if the costs in human terms are uncomfortable.'
There was some concern, however, that the proposals might jeopardise the
tradition at the Treasury that promising young officials can expect a series
of promotions to the higher echelons of the department over an unbroken
civil service career.
A long-standing Treasury official said: 'Anyone in the bottom layers and who
saw themselves as having a job for life is bound to be disappointed. But I
suppose this is exactly what's happened to tens of thousands of others
outside the department.'
Another concern is officials in their forties and fifties, just below the
top layer in the Treasury and so not well enough connected to land senior
jobs in private industry, yet too old to take on jobs for youthful
high-fliers that might be on offer in the City.
But as officials digested the implications of the proposals there was even
time for some grudging admiration for Mr Jeremy Heywood, the young Treasury
official who masterminded the review. 'He's razor sharp, an absolutely
brilliant individual who could get a job virtually anywhere,' said one
Treasury man whose own future at the department is in doubt.
</TEXT>
