<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Civil Service Reorganisation: Shaping up for a radical
reorientation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The radical report on the Treasury's 'fundamental expenditure review of
running costs', published yesterday with a broad endorsement by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, recommends that a quarter of the department's top
jobs should go by next April.
Sir Terry Burns, the Treasury's permanent secretary, is frank. 'We shall
have a difficult and stressful period ahead,' he wrote to staff yesterday.
One senior official likened the impact of the report to the visit of the
International Monetary Fund in 1976, the crisis year of the last Labour
government.
The review proposes that the number of senior management posts in the
Treasury be cut from 99 to 72 by next April. The knock-on effect will be
significant in the lower grades which account for most of the Treasury's
1,400 staff.
Behind the cuts lies a radical reorientation of the Treasury's activities.
The number of directorates will be reduced from nine to seven, with a lesser
emphasis on economic forecasting - which Mr Clarke insists should be
market-tested in two years' time - and a big reduction in the effort the
Treasury makes to shadow the spending departments. The review also proposes
a mission statement for the first time.
Even Conservatives close to the Treasury are divided about the plans. Mr
Andrew Tyrie, an adviser to both Lord Lawson and Mr John Major in their
periods as chancellor, said: 'Unlike much of the civil service the Treasury
ain't broken, so there must be doubts about the wisdom of such a fundamental
cull.'
By contrast, Mr Graham Mather, president of the European Policy Forum and a
Tory MEP, said the proposals represented a 'historic opportunity' to reshape
Whitehall and strip out unnecessary administrative tiers. He likened the
review to the revolutionary Treasury-driven reform process in New Zealand,
which has led to senior officials serving on individual contracts tied to
performance targets.
For most observers the key issue is whether the reforms will limit the
Treasury's capacity to control the spending departments. The review insists
that the Treasury must 'continue to exercise the firmest possible control
over public expenditure' but can do so without the 'current panoply of
detailed controls over departmental gifts, ex gratia payments, projects and
so on.'
Some Treasury insiders are doubtful. 'It's a shame Terry Burns was not
around when the IMF came in 1976 - then he would know why the controls are
necessary,' said one.
</TEXT>
