FT  20 OCT 94 / Commons body chairman elected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Thomas Arnold, Tory MP for Hazel Grove and a former vice-chairman of the
Conservative party, was yesterday elected chairman of the influential
Treasury and civil service committee of MPs.
The move was seen as a boost for the body's independence from government. Mr
Nigel Forman, the MP for Carshalton and Wallington, is understood to have
been the preferred candidate of government business managers.
The vacancy arose because of the appointment of Mr John Watts, the previous
incumbent, as transport minister.
Sir Thomas said that he would regard his first duty as upholding the
independence and integrity of the committee.
He said he would wish to consult members regularly. It was 'very important
that the chairman makes a conscious effort to talk to members individually
to address any concerns and to seek their advice.'
Sir Thomas faces a delicate task balancing the views of members ranging from
Labour's Ms Diane Abbott on the left to the Tories' Mr Barry Legg on the
right.
