<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 94 / Police quell riot outside Commons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Police guarding the House of Commons were bombarded with bottles, sticks and
fire crackers last night as they quelled a riot by opponents of the criminal
justice and public order bill, Ivor Owen writes.
The rioters tried to storm the main gates used by ministers and MPs and
police were forced to use batons to disperse them.
All the entrances to the Commons and the Lords were closed. MPs and
officials were prevented from leaving for more than an hour.
Before the riot reached its full intensity the government bowed to the view
of the Lords and strengthened the safeguards for defendants who exercise the
modified right to silence - one of the most significant changes introduced
by the bill.
It was one of the few amendments made to the bill by peers which the
government agreed to accept.
Under pressure from law lords and other peers Mr Michael Howard, home
secretary, accepted the need for a revised caution emphasising that juries
would be entitled to draw inferences from a defendant's refusal to respond
to police questioning.
The proposed version reads: 'You do not have to say anything. But if you do
not mention now something which you later use in your defence, the court may
decide that your failure to mention it now strengthens the case against you.
A record will be made of anything you say and it may be given in evidence if
you are brought to court.'
</TEXT>
